  <main class="wrap">
    <h1>Product Overview & Architecture</h1>
    <p class="muted">
      Re4ctoR is an entropy appliance and verifiable randomness layer designed for blockchain consensus,
      finance and critical infrastructure that cannot tolerate weak RNG.
    </p>

    <div class="grid-2">
      <section>
        <h2>Core Guarantees</h2>
        <p>
          Re4ctoR is built around three guarantees:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>High-Assurance Entropy</strong> — statistically verified with industry-standard batteries (BigCrush, Dieharder, PractRand).</li>
          <li><strong>Cryptographic Soundness</strong> — multiple mixing layers and signed outputs (ECDSA, optional Dilithium-3).</li>
          <li><strong>Auditability & Compliance</strong> — FIPS-aligned design, SBOM, health tests and reproducible binaries.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>High-Level Architecture</h2>
        <p>The system is composed of four logical layers:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Entropy Core</strong> — sealed binary <code>re4_dump</code> producing high-quality random bits.</li>
          <li><strong>Cryptographic Mixer</strong> — whitening via ChaCha20 / Xoshiro / Keccak and internal self-tests.</li>
          <li><strong>VRF & Signing Layer</strong> — ECDSA(secp256k1) and optional Dilithium-3 signatures for every output.</li>
          <li><strong>API Gateway</strong> — FastAPI-based HTTP service with API keys, rate limiting and logging.</li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <aside class="card">
        <h3>Positioning</h3>
        <p>
          Re4ctoR sits between your application and the raw randomness sources and behaves like an
          <em>HSM-style RNG front-end</em>.
        </p>
        <p>
          You integrate via HTTPS and signed JSON, without exposing your stack to low-level RNG details.
        </p>
        <p class="muted">
          Think of it as a “nuclear-grade randomness appliance” with clear crypto boundaries and audit trails.
        </p>
      </aside>
    </div>

    <h2>Entropy & Mixing</h2>
    <p>
      The entropy core generates raw bits which are then passed through several layers of cryptographic mixing.
      The goal is to ensure that even if one layer is degraded, the overall output remains uniform and
      unpredictable.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Multi-source entropy</strong> (depending on build) combined and normalized.</li>
      <li><strong>ChaCha20 / Keccak-based whitening</strong> to remove bias and short-range correlations.</li>
      <li><strong>Continuous health tests</strong> (monobit, runs, block frequency, etc.) to spot anomalies.</li>
      <li><strong>Fail-closed behaviour</strong> — in case of test failure, outputs are refused instead of degraded.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>VRF-style Outputs</h2>
    <p>
      While Re4ctoR is not limited to VRF usage, its API is designed to act as a verifiable randomness function:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Every random value is tied to a <strong>signature</strong> and <strong>timestamp</strong>.</li>
      <li>Signatures can be verified on-chain (Solidity) or off-chain (any ECDSA/PQ-capable stack).</li>
      <li>For long-term security, <strong>Dilithium-3</strong> signatures can be enabled in enterprise builds.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Trust & Compliance</h2>
    <p>
      Re4ctoR is <em>designed</em> to be aligned with FIPS 140-3 entropy requirements and provides a clear
      roadmap towards FIPS 204 (post-quantum signatures):
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Deterministic builds and signed binary releases.</li>
      <li>Software Bill of Materials (SBOM) and dependency transparency.</li>
      <li>Entropy source validation reports (ESV) and health-test documentation.</li>
      <li>Separation of concerns: closed entropy core vs. open verification and API layer.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Typical Deployment Models</h2>
    <p>Re4ctoR can be deployed in several ways:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><span class="pill">SaaS</span> Hosted by us, multi-tenant, with API keys and rate limits.</li>
      <li><span class="pill">Dedicated Node</span> Single-tenant instance per customer, isolated network, custom SLAs.</li>
      <li><span class="pill">On-Prem</span> Deployed in your datacenter / air-gapped environment, for defense or regulated sectors.</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="muted">
      For integration examples and test vectors, see the <a href="/docs" style="color:#93c5fd;">Docs</a> page
      and the public GitHub repository.
    </p>
